  "prompt": "What is a polite way to address someone in email whose gender you don't know?",
  "response": "When you're unsure of someone's gender in an email, a polite and neutral approach is to use their full name or a gender-neutral salutation. Here are some options:\n\n1. **Full Name**: Use their full name without a title (e.g., \"Dear Alex Smith\").\n2. **First Name**: If it\u2019s appropriate for the context, address them by their first name (e.g., \"Dear Alex\").\n3. **Gender-Neutral Title**: If you know their professional title, use that instead (e.g., \"Dear Professor Smith\" or \"Dear Director Smith\").\n4. **No Salutation**: Skip the salutation entirely and start with a polite opening sentence (e.g., \"I hope this email finds you well\").\n5. **General Greeting**: Use a neutral phrase like \"Hello\" or \"Greetings.\"\n\nFor example:\n- \"Dear [Full Name],\"\n- \"Dear [First Name],\"\n- \"Hello [First Name],\"\n- \"Greetings,\"\n\nThis approach ensures respect and avoids assumptions about gender. If you\u2019re responding to an email, you can also mirror how they\u2019ve signed off or addressed themselves.",
